05982nam a22007695i 9780292757363DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20211981txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927573637 a10.7560/7035202doi  a(DE-B1597)587160  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGR110.T5bA52 7aSOC0110002bisacsh04a398/.0976421904aAnd Other Neighborly Names :bSocial Process and Cultural Image in Texas Folklore /ced. by Roger D. Abrahams, Richard Bauman. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1981  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tContents -- tI. Introduction -- tDoing Folklore Texas-Style -- tII. The Structure and Context of Expressive Forms The Caso -- tAn Emic Genre of Folk Narrative -- tThe Corrido of Greater Mexico as Discourse, Music, and Event -- tIII. Social Types and Stereotypes -- t"Any Man Who Keeps More'n One Hound'11 Lie to You": Dog Trading and Storytelling at Canton, Texas -- t"Guess How Doughnuts Are Made": Verbal and Nonverbal Aspects of the Panadero and His Stereotype -- tCowboys and Clowns: Rodeo Specialists and the Ideology of Work and Play -- tAustins Cosmic Cowboys: Words in Collision -- tIV Expressive Dimensions of Heterogeneity and Change -- tThe Folk Performance of "Chicano" and the Cultural Limits of Political Ideology -- tFolklore and Ethnic Identity in Tigua Nativism -- tTension and Speech Play in Mexican-American Folklore -- tA Traditional Storyteller in Changing Contexts -- tThe Emergence of Conjunto Music, 1935-1955 -- tV. Conclusion: A Look toward Future Concerns -- tShouting Match at the Border: The Folklore of Display Events -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"And Other Neighborly Names"—the title is from a study by Americo Paredes of the names, complimentary and otherwise, exchanged across cultural boundaries by Anglos and Mexicans—is a collection of essays devoted to various aspects of folk tradition in Texas. The approach builds on the work of the folklorists who have helped give the study of folklore in Texas such high standing in the field-Mody Boatright, J. Frank Dobie, John Mason Brewer, the Lomaxes, and of course Paredes himself, to whom this book is dedicated. Focusing on the ways in which traditions arise and are maintained where diverse peoples come together, the editors and other essayists—John Holmes McDowell, Joe Graham, Alicia María González, Beverly J. Stoeltje, Archie Green, José E. Limón, Thomas A. Green, Rosan A. Jordan, Patrick B. Mullen, and Manuel H. Peña—examine conjunto music, the corrido, Gulf fishermen's stories, rodeo traditions, dog trading and dog-trading tales, Mexican bakers' lore, Austin's "cosmic cowboy" scene, and other fascinating aspects of folklore in Texas. Their emphasis is on the creative reaction to socially and culturally pluralistic situations, and in this they represent a distinctively Texan way of studying folklore, especially as illustrated in the performance-centered approach of Paredes, Boatright, and others who taught at the University of Texas at Austin. As an overview of this approach—its past, present, and future—"And Other Neighborly Names" makes a valuable contribution both to Texas folklore and to the discipline as a whole.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aFolklorezTexas. 0aTexas--Social life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh1 aAbrahams, Roger D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAbrahams, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauman, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://i